FINALLY! The mobile classrooms have arrived and lessons have resumed at the Sediba Sa Thuto Primary School in Extension 18 in Mamelodi East, Tshwane. Thanks to Sunpower,The Daily Sun published the story after angry parents shut down the school in May due to overcrowding. As schools reopened across the country on Tuesday, 19 July, the pupils at the school were welcomed by three new mobile classrooms. Happy parents said their children will now be able to go back to their lessons. School Governing Body (SGB) chairwoman Tebogo Selemela said the mobile classrooms were delivered on Monday, 18 July. She said they need two more classrooms. “We are so happy and relieved that the classes will reduce overcrowding,” she said. “Overcrowding has affected us for many years. “Our children were denied education for almost two months because parents wanted more classrooms,” she said. Selemela said the school has 36 mobile classrooms and 1 862 pupils. Some classes have over 70 pupils, which is beyond the required number. Concerned parents’ representative, Thulani Mabena (40), said: “We are happy but we are still waiting for proper classrooms.” He said they are still waiting for two mobile classrooms and two mobile toilets. Thulani said it’s good to see children back in class and the mobile classrooms will assist with the overcrowding. Democratic Alliance (DA) Gauteng shadow MEC for education, Khume Ramulifho said: “We are happy to see the pupils back at school. It is unfortunate that pupils stayed home for so many weeks.”  The DA is urging parents to support pupils and teachers to ensure that they can complete the curriculum All the best to Sediba Sa Thuto pupils.” Gauteng education spokesman Steve Mabona said: “We’re happy that schooling is continuing and call on members of the community not to disrupt schooling.”